1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:02,240
Hi, I'm Anton Denisov.

2
00:00:02,450 --> 00:00:03,890
I work at the Dwelli.

3
00:00:03,999 --> 00:00:09,780
It's a tech native real estate operator in
the UK where I lead the revenue function

4
00:00:09,819 --> 00:00:12,990
and built our product and data systems.

5
00:00:13,020 --> 00:00:16,680
Today, I'm talking about a
sentiment analysis system that

6
00:00:16,680 --> 00:00:18,250
we build and run in production.

7
00:00:19,009 --> 00:00:24,290
It reads landlord emails and phone calls
and flags the ones where the customer is

8
00:00:24,290 --> 00:00:27,130
unhappy, so we can act before they leave.

9
00:00:27,630 --> 00:00:30,770
I'll cover how we built it, the
data, the model, and what we found

10
00:00:31,270 --> 00:00:34,210
Dwell is a tech native real
estate operator in the UK.

11
00:00:34,220 --> 00:00:39,220
In plain terms, we manage rental
properties end to end on behalf of

12
00:00:39,230 --> 00:00:43,960
the landlords thousands of them on
our own software stack rather than

13
00:00:43,960 --> 00:00:45,270
a traditional high street agency.

14
00:00:45,770 --> 00:00:49,190
This talk is about a system we
built and run in production.

15
00:00:49,760 --> 00:00:53,980
It reads our landlord communications,
emails, and phone calls, and flags the

16
00:00:53,980 --> 00:00:58,170
ones where the landlord is unhappy,
so we can step in before they leave.

17
00:00:59,010 --> 00:01:02,930
I'll walk through how we built it, the
data, the model, the prompt engineering,

18
00:01:03,439 --> 00:01:08,370
which took most of the time and work
we learned running it on real messy

19
00:01:08,370 --> 00:01:14,040
conversations The title promises British
sarcasms, and that's a real problem.

20
00:01:14,130 --> 00:01:14,970
I'll get to it.

21
00:01:15,520 --> 00:01:19,150
The harder question sitting
underneath is the engineering.

22
00:01:19,920 --> 00:01:24,500
How do you build a sentiment system
that actually works when your customers

23
00:01:24,500 --> 00:01:29,200
are real people on the phone who
don't always say what they mean?

24
00:01:30,010 --> 00:01:32,720
Here is a core problem
in a single message.

25
00:01:33,430 --> 00:01:36,390
Our landlord wrote to
us, "No problem at all.

26
00:01:36,860 --> 00:01:38,730
I completely understand your visit.

27
00:01:39,340 --> 00:01:42,360
Whenever you get a chance to look
in the boiler, that would be great.

28
00:01:42,890 --> 00:01:47,480
Thank you so much for all your help."
Run through most of the off-the-shelf

29
00:01:47,480 --> 00:01:53,050
sentiment models, and it scores positive;
no problem, great, thank you so much.

30
00:01:53,550 --> 00:01:56,320
However, i- and it looks
like a happy customer.

31
00:01:56,820 --> 00:02:00,720
That landlord moved their
property to a competitor about two

32
00:02:00,720 --> 00:02:02,360
weeks later after this message.

33
00:02:03,010 --> 00:02:06,370
A generic model would
never have flagged it.

34
00:02:07,120 --> 00:02:11,040
Building something that does
is the subject of this talk.

35
00:02:11,540 --> 00:02:12,750
A bit of context first.

36
00:02:13,570 --> 00:02:16,500
Retention drives the
economics of this business.

37
00:02:16,939 --> 00:02:21,250
A managed property is a multi-year
recurring relationship, and

38
00:02:21,250 --> 00:02:25,349
replacing a lo-lost landlord
costs far more than keeping one.

39
00:02:26,030 --> 00:02:29,610
You are paying acquisition
costs again just to stand still.

40
00:02:30,110 --> 00:02:32,610
One thing surprised us
when we looked closely.

41
00:02:33,090 --> 00:02:37,380
A big part of churn is
unpreventable, though not most of it.

42
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:42,810
Landlords sell the flat or they
move back in themselves, and for

43
00:02:42,810 --> 00:02:46,530
a real share of cases, nothing we
did would have changed the outcome.

44
00:02:47,030 --> 00:02:52,210
If you're ever handed a reduced churn
target, that's w- worth knowing upfront.

45
00:02:52,500 --> 00:02:54,400
It stop you chasing the wrong number.

46
00:02:54,900 --> 00:03:00,090
But the rest of it, landlords switching
to competitor or deciding to manage

47
00:03:00,090 --> 00:03:04,860
properties themselves, it's service
driven and therefore preventable.

48
00:03:05,790 --> 00:03:07,610
It's also the expensive kind.

49
00:03:07,620 --> 00:03:12,599
It reflects disfact-- dissatisfaction
rather than a live rent.

50
00:03:13,250 --> 00:03:15,960
Those are the people you
actually have a chance to keep.

51
00:03:16,460 --> 00:03:19,889
So the problem wasn't
really measure sentiment.

52
00:03:20,309 --> 00:03:21,330
It was narrower.

53
00:03:21,889 --> 00:03:26,320
Can we detect the preventable
churn early enough to act on it

54
00:03:26,919 --> 00:03:32,600
inside tens of thousands of mostly
ordinary, mostly polite interactions?

55
00:03:33,100 --> 00:03:37,030
The signals we needed were
rare, and they were easy to miss

56
00:03:37,530 --> 00:03:42,270
Standard sentiment analysis,
lexicon scoring, classic fine-tuning

57
00:03:42,270 --> 00:03:47,640
classifiers, NPS surveys, all
rest on the same assumption, that

58
00:03:47,640 --> 00:03:52,300
the strength of the emotion words
track the strength of the feeling.

59
00:03:53,060 --> 00:03:57,420
More terrible, more furious,
more explanation marks, the

60
00:03:57,420 --> 00:03:59,220
more negatives in messages.

61
00:04:00,170 --> 00:04:03,410
British professional communication
doesn't follow that rule.

62
00:04:04,110 --> 00:04:07,700
A lot of complaint here is
expressed by removing the

63
00:04:07,700 --> 00:04:09,640
emotional signal, not adding it.

64
00:04:10,140 --> 00:04:14,350
A few real examples: " I'd have thought
someone would have called me back by

65
00:04:14,350 --> 00:04:19,330
now." That's a complaint. " A little
disappointed with how this was handled."

66
00:04:19,900 --> 00:04:21,610
A little usually means quite a lot.

67
00:04:22,530 --> 00:04:27,250
"When you get a chance" often means
this is urgent and already overdue.

68
00:04:27,750 --> 00:04:31,370
The dissatisfaction is fully
present in all the three.

69
00:04:32,160 --> 00:04:37,220
It just been toned down because
saying it directly would feel rude.

70
00:04:37,720 --> 00:04:42,720
And the keyword model reads every
one of them as neutral or positive.

71
00:04:43,190 --> 00:04:45,330
There is no angry words to catch.

72
00:04:45,840 --> 00:04:48,570
NPS makes it worse, not better.

73
00:04:49,160 --> 00:04:53,320
The people most likely to quietly
leave are exactly the ones who are

74
00:04:53,370 --> 00:04:55,270
too polite to give you a low score.

75
00:04:55,920 --> 00:04:58,720
They give you seven, and
they then don't renew.

76
00:04:59,220 --> 00:05:04,380
There is a second half to this that's easy
to overlook, and it matters just as much.

77
00:05:05,050 --> 00:05:09,270
A large share of the dissatisfaction
wasn't caused by something we did.

78
00:05:09,630 --> 00:05:11,950
It was caused by something we didn't do.

79
00:05:12,870 --> 00:05:17,300
Silence on our side, and landlord
emails that no one replies.

80
00:05:17,810 --> 00:05:20,600
They leave a voicemail, no one calls back.

81
00:05:21,100 --> 00:05:24,270
They chase, and the chase goes unanswered.

82
00:05:24,770 --> 00:05:29,040
From the model's point of view,
that's a hard case because the

83
00:05:29,100 --> 00:05:31,660
triggering event is an absence.

84
00:05:32,090 --> 00:05:37,140
There is no angry message to classify,
just a follow-up that is slightly shorter

85
00:05:37,390 --> 00:05:39,169
or slightly cooler than the last one.

86
00:05:39,920 --> 00:05:42,819
But it was one of the biggest
drivers of churn we had.

87
00:05:43,629 --> 00:05:47,220
People often don't leave because
they got something wrong.

88
00:05:47,930 --> 00:05:49,920
People leave because we went quiet.

89
00:05:50,590 --> 00:05:53,290
So the task was never detect anger.

90
00:05:53,910 --> 00:05:55,340
Anger is the easy case.

91
00:05:55,370 --> 00:05:56,880
It announces itself.

92
00:05:57,310 --> 00:06:01,280
The real task was to detect
dissatisfaction that has been deliberately

93
00:06:01,340 --> 00:06:07,819
understated, and in some cases to
infer it from what wasn't said or what

94
00:06:07,820 --> 00:06:12,040
wasn't done Let me walk you through
the dataset, because this is where

95
00:06:12,040 --> 00:06:14,250
the introduction starts to matter.

96
00:06:15,050 --> 00:06:20,370
We pulled together around eleven
thousand landlord interactions over

97
00:06:20,370 --> 00:06:24,260
about a seven-week window, roughly
two thousand unique landlords.

98
00:06:24,540 --> 00:06:28,370
It spanned four channels, and
the channel mattered a lot, so

99
00:06:28,370 --> 00:06:29,760
these are worth holding onto.

100
00:06:30,260 --> 00:06:33,520
Email through our CRM,
structured and logged.

101
00:06:34,480 --> 00:06:38,870
Email outside the CRM, and landlord
just emails the person directly.

102
00:06:39,560 --> 00:06:43,820
Calls through the CRM, usually
our team calling the landlord.

103
00:06:44,350 --> 00:06:48,400
And an inbound calls outside
the CRM, where the landlord pick

104
00:06:48,400 --> 00:06:50,669
ups up the phone and rings us.

105
00:06:51,549 --> 00:06:55,640
The calls were the most valuable
and the hardest to work with.

106
00:06:56,280 --> 00:06:59,550
About eleven hundred of them
transcribed with Voximplant.

107
00:07:00,380 --> 00:07:04,600
People are more candid on the phone
than in writing, though that's where

108
00:07:04,640 --> 00:07:06,640
a lot of the real signal lived.

109
00:07:07,460 --> 00:07:13,040
But the transcripts are messy:
overlapping speakers, tangents, speech

110
00:07:13,040 --> 00:07:14,930
recognition error, no structure.

111
00:07:15,360 --> 00:07:17,690
If you work with the call
data, you know it's a different

112
00:07:17,690 --> 00:07:19,209
problem from a clean text.

113
00:07:20,070 --> 00:07:25,099
Then labeling, which I which I would
encourage any team to overinvest in.

114
00:07:25,729 --> 00:07:28,279
We did not start by prompting the model.

115
00:07:28,419 --> 00:07:29,819
We started by reading.

116
00:07:30,239 --> 00:07:33,839
We hand-labeled around two hundred
borderline negative cases from the

117
00:07:33,839 --> 00:07:38,160
actual transcripts, and we wrote
label definitions as explicit

118
00:07:38,169 --> 00:07:40,539
decision rules, not judgment calls.

119
00:07:41,320 --> 00:07:46,609
The schema had three axes: severity,
four levels, green, amber, orange,

120
00:07:46,619 --> 00:07:50,810
red; topic, maintenance, payments,
move-out, compliance, seven find

121
00:07:50,810 --> 00:07:55,330
or other; and intent, about ten
categories, and this is where most

122
00:07:55,330 --> 00:07:59,189
of the value was: communication,
failure, self-management, signal,

123
00:07:59,199 --> 00:08:01,679
decision, dispute, et cetera, et cetera.

124
00:08:02,179 --> 00:08:05,010
The severity rules were
deliberately mechanical.

125
00:08:05,749 --> 00:08:07,799
Amber need an explicit signal.

126
00:08:08,390 --> 00:08:10,750
Orange need two independent strong signal.

127
00:08:11,140 --> 00:08:14,060
Red needs literal termination language.

128
00:08:14,820 --> 00:08:18,620
We wrote them that a way for a
reason-- that way for a reason.

129
00:08:19,050 --> 00:08:23,819
So two different people would land on
the same label and saw the model would

130
00:08:23,820 --> 00:08:26,320
match the humans rather than drift.

131
00:08:27,150 --> 00:08:29,930
That hand label set did double duty.

132
00:08:30,300 --> 00:08:35,600
It was both our evaluation benchmark
and our source of few short examples

133
00:08:36,100 --> 00:08:40,230
We used this language model, a large
language model, Cloth Sonnet, and the most

134
00:08:40,230 --> 00:08:45,620
important design decision was to make it
as two-step pipeline rather than one shot.

135
00:08:46,280 --> 00:08:47,630
Step one is narrow.

136
00:08:48,330 --> 00:08:50,160
Is this message negative at all?

137
00:08:50,970 --> 00:08:55,030
A three-way call: positive,
neutral, negative, nothing else.

138
00:08:55,590 --> 00:08:59,940
Step two runs only on the message
that come back negative, about

139
00:08:59,940 --> 00:09:01,990
six or seven percent of the total.

140
00:09:02,640 --> 00:09:07,360
On those and only on those, we extract
the full structure, severity topic

141
00:09:07,370 --> 00:09:08,970
intent, and the routing decision.

142
00:09:09,730 --> 00:09:11,880
There are two reason to this matters.

143
00:09:12,360 --> 00:09:14,630
The first is the cost and latency.

144
00:09:15,010 --> 00:09:18,940
Step two is expensive reasoning,
and you run on seven percent of

145
00:09:18,940 --> 00:09:20,530
the volume instead of all of it.

146
00:09:21,080 --> 00:09:25,500
The whole pipeline came in
around a third cent per message.

147
00:09:26,460 --> 00:09:28,930
The re- the second
reason is more important.

148
00:09:29,280 --> 00:09:34,190
Splitting the steps let us tune
recall on direction separately

149
00:09:34,490 --> 00:09:36,430
from precision of classification.

150
00:09:37,380 --> 00:09:39,010
Those are different objectives.

151
00:09:39,390 --> 00:09:42,980
Trying to hit both in a
single prompt made both worse.

152
00:09:43,860 --> 00:09:47,710
Once they were separate, we could make
the detector deliberately sensitive

153
00:09:48,170 --> 00:09:52,810
by store catching the quiet, polite
cases, while keeping the severity

154
00:09:52,810 --> 00:09:59,869
classifier conservative, so it doesn't
turn every mild grumble into the red

155
00:09:59,940 --> 00:10:04,400
alert Then the prompt engineering,
where the real interaction went.

156
00:10:04,870 --> 00:10:08,880
Three problems worth naming
because I suspect they generalize.

157
00:10:09,800 --> 00:10:12,840
One, the model rewi-rewarded politeness.

158
00:10:13,480 --> 00:10:16,630
Out of the box, it did exactly
what the keyword models do.

159
00:10:16,880 --> 00:10:21,270
They saw lovely, thank you so
much, and scored it positive.

160
00:10:21,830 --> 00:10:24,600
The fix was to tell it to treat
the courtesy as a wrapping and

161
00:10:24,600 --> 00:10:26,500
classify on the substance underneath.

162
00:10:27,140 --> 00:10:29,110
What is this person actually asking for?

163
00:10:29,390 --> 00:10:31,500
How many times have
they had to ask for it?

164
00:10:31,910 --> 00:10:34,180
Is the politeness covering frustration?

165
00:10:34,840 --> 00:10:38,540
Then we fed in the hand-labeled
polite but negative case a few

166
00:10:38,540 --> 00:10:43,219
short anchors, concrete examples
of sounds nice is not nice.

167
00:10:43,719 --> 00:10:47,120
That only… That one change moved the
results from anything else we did…

168
00:10:47,160 --> 00:10:48,269
more than anything else we did.

169
00:10:48,769 --> 00:10:51,679
Two, problem number
two, it over-escalated.

170
00:10:52,639 --> 00:10:57,229
A sensitive detector wants to label
everything orange, so it pushed the

171
00:10:57,229 --> 00:10:59,099
strict rules straight into the prompt.

172
00:10:59,539 --> 00:11:01,709
Orange requires two strong signals.

173
00:11:01,739 --> 00:11:05,769
Red requires explicit language
and nothing else, nothing less.

174
00:11:06,499 --> 00:11:10,679
Severity became a checklist,
not a feeling, and the

175
00:11:10,679 --> 00:11:12,939
false red largely went away.

176
00:11:13,439 --> 00:11:16,389
Three, telling went in apart from blame.

177
00:11:16,889 --> 00:11:22,369
Landlords would call up annoyed about a
tenant or a contractor or some external

178
00:11:22,369 --> 00:11:25,709
mess and explicitly not blame us.

179
00:11:26,039 --> 00:11:27,229
I know it's not your fault.

180
00:11:27,909 --> 00:11:32,369
A naive classifier reads a negative
tone and routes it to a ser-service

181
00:11:32,369 --> 00:11:36,469
failure, and a manager spends
their afternoon apologizing for

182
00:11:36,469 --> 00:11:38,309
something they did not cause.

183
00:11:38,749 --> 00:11:43,659
So external issue became its own
intent, and the prompt had to separate

184
00:11:43,669 --> 00:11:48,499
two things that look identical to
a keyword model, the tone of the

185
00:11:48,499 --> 00:11:50,459
message and who it's aimed it at.

186
00:11:51,289 --> 00:11:54,669
Negative but not at us is a
completely different action.

187
00:11:55,169 --> 00:12:00,079
On the production side, none of
these were one-off batch job.

188
00:12:00,609 --> 00:12:05,820
Emails streamed in from BigQuery, calls
came through Voximplant translation,

189
00:12:05,830 --> 00:12:09,670
the models scored continuously, and
the scores were written back into the

190
00:12:09,670 --> 00:12:13,489
warehouse for the rest of the business
to use So what were the key findings?

191
00:12:13,799 --> 00:12:18,719
First, people are more guarded in
writing and more direct on the phone.

192
00:12:19,359 --> 00:12:24,909
Calls ran meaningfully more negative
than email in order of 50% more.

193
00:12:25,769 --> 00:12:31,879
Second, and no survey tool can do this,
switching channels is a leading indicator.

194
00:12:32,629 --> 00:12:36,049
When a landlord who'd been emailing
us suddenly starts phoning,

195
00:12:36,139 --> 00:12:37,819
escalation usually follows.

196
00:12:38,269 --> 00:12:40,429
The switch itself is a signal.

197
00:12:40,929 --> 00:12:45,989
Third, communication failure was
the single largest category, about

198
00:12:45,999 --> 00:12:48,799
36% of all negative interactions.

199
00:12:49,089 --> 00:12:52,929
Not maintenance, not money, not
being able to reach a human.

200
00:12:53,559 --> 00:12:57,899
More than a third of neg- every negative
case reduced to, "I tried to contact

201
00:12:57,899 --> 00:13:04,699
you, nothing happened." Fourth, the
polite customer point, now with numbers.

202
00:13:05,169 --> 00:13:08,809
We match the sentiment data against
the landlords who actually left.

203
00:13:09,369 --> 00:13:13,469
The ones who left to sell
ran around 4% negativity.

204
00:13:14,169 --> 00:13:18,749
The ones who switched to a competitor,
the preventable, expensive chore, ran

205
00:13:18,789 --> 00:13:24,129
several times higher But here's what
matters for how you build the model.

206
00:13:24,489 --> 00:13:26,269
They didn't express it by shouting.

207
00:13:26,329 --> 00:13:30,239
They expressed it by in measured,
polite, slightly formal language.

208
00:13:30,739 --> 00:13:35,369
And the fifth, the more data
sources mean b- better output.

209
00:13:35,979 --> 00:13:40,839
One agency looked like the top
performer, very low negativity, about 4%.

210
00:13:41,729 --> 00:13:42,999
Then we checked the pipeline.

211
00:13:43,249 --> 00:13:46,089
We were only capturing a small
fraction of that agency calls.

212
00:13:46,109 --> 00:13:49,359
Most of its phone conversation
were not reaching the model at all.

213
00:13:50,219 --> 00:13:53,269
Once the call feed was complete,
the number fell right in

214
00:13:53,269 --> 00:13:54,579
line with everyone else's.

215
00:13:54,919 --> 00:13:56,189
So the point is simple.

216
00:13:56,439 --> 00:13:59,929
The quality of the output is
bounded by the coverage of the input

217
00:14:00,429 --> 00:14:02,999
Detection on its own doesn't do much.

218
00:14:03,909 --> 00:14:07,819
A classifier that produces a
dashboard nobody acts is just

219
00:14:07,819 --> 00:14:09,309
a report with extra steps.

220
00:14:10,049 --> 00:14:13,619
So each intent mapped it to a
defined action, what an owner and

221
00:14:13,619 --> 00:14:16,439
response time agreed in advance
with the people who'd carry it out.

222
00:14:16,969 --> 00:14:20,909
Communication failure, a manager
calls within twenty-four hours.

223
00:14:20,999 --> 00:14:25,199
A self-management signal, a personal
call, a conversation about the value, not

224
00:14:25,199 --> 00:14:27,759
specific repair, et cetera, et cetera.

225
00:14:28,669 --> 00:14:33,819
The cleanest example of the loop closing,
once we quantified that communication

226
00:14:33,849 --> 00:14:38,089
fai-failure was the single biggest
driver, chasing landlords one by

227
00:14:38,089 --> 00:14:40,609
one was obviously treating symptoms.

228
00:14:41,109 --> 00:14:42,539
The cause was structural.

229
00:14:42,969 --> 00:14:45,329
We were not answering
the call, phone reliably.

230
00:14:45,719 --> 00:14:50,019
So the finding led directly to a second
build, an agentic voice assistant

231
00:14:50,029 --> 00:14:52,059
to handle inbound landlord calls.

232
00:14:52,839 --> 00:14:56,689
The detection system didn't just flag
